Automatic detection of malaria from erythrocytes: Optimization of a deep learning CNN model. Final Submission¶

Julia A. Moffitt, PhD

Problem Definition

The context:

  • Malaria continues to exact an enormous global health burden, despite a clear understanding of mechanisms, method of detection and means for prevention and treatment (5).
  • Despite global trends in reducing case incidence rate, progress towards milestones has reversed in some areas, particularly in Sub-Saharan Africa, where rates of malaria are among the highest (5).
  • Countries with the highest rates of malaria have the fewest economic resources to devote to tackling the problem (5).
  • Disruptions in resource allocations due to COVID have also impeded progress (5).
  • Rapid, accurate detection of malaria is important as delays in diagnosis and treatment increase mortality.
  • Malaria is caused by parasitic transmission of the Plasmodium group through infected mosquito bites (3).
  • Malaria has traditionally been diagnosed through manual microscopic examination of stained blood smears, a tedious process dependent on trained operators and prone to error (3).
  • Recent advances in AI an computer vision technology have enabled the detection of malaria through automated means (1-4).
  • Despite these advances, use of peripheral blood smear remains the primary means of diagnosing malaria (1).
  • Ideally, a method by which automatic visual inspection of parasitized erythrocytes (red blood cells; RBCs) deployed on a smartphone would allow for rapid diagnosis in any setting (1,2).

The overall goal of this project is to contribute to maximizing malaria detection through development of deep learning models, while minimizing computational resource needs.

The objective of this project is to build on currently established CNN deep learning models for the detection of malaria in RBCs to optimize the model to reduce computing resources while maintaining a high level of accuracy.

The key questions:

  • Can an accurate CNN model be developed that can be deployed with minimal computational needs? (i.e. from a smartphone)
  • Does training the model with a correctly labeled data set lead to better performance?
  • What are the ideal parmameters to use for the model?
  • Do the data need augmentation or is it not necessary?

The problem formulation:

  • Correctly identifying and classifying images of RBCs as either parasitized or uninfected with malaria is the key objective in development of this model. Becuase this is a medical diagnostic use, it is imperative that the model perform with extremely high accuracy and very low error.

  • The overall goal is to construct a highly effective model that uses as few layers and computational resources necessary so it may deployed on smartphones for use in remote areas in countries with fewer resources.

Data Description

  • In the original assignmnet there were a total of 24,958 train and 2,600 test images (colored) that were taken from microscopic images.

  • Prior to initiating the project a literature search on PubMed was conducted. Within that search an article by Fuhad et. al. 2020 took the above data set and cleaned and correctly labeled it with the assistance of an expert (2). Some ambigouous images were removed and others had labels corrected. This resulted in 13,029 uninfected and 13,132 parasitized images.

  • It is the goal of this project to use the correctly labeled and updated data set in the development of the model. Corrected Malaria Data—Google Drive. [(accessed on 29 December 2019)];2019 Available online: https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/10TXXa6B_D4AKuBV085tX7UudH1hINBRJ?usp=sharing.

These images are of the following categories:

Parasitized: The parasitized cells contain the Plasmodium parasite which causes malaria Uninfected: The uninfected cells are free of the Plasmodium parasites

# function to find the mean
def find_mean_img(full_mat, title):
    # calculate the average
    mean_img = np.mean(full_mat, axis = 0)[0]
    # reshape it back to a matrix
    plt.imshow(mean_img)
    plt.title(f'Average {title}')
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.show()
    return mean_img

The shape of the data is critical to forming the correct configuration of the input layer to the CNN. The shape shows the correct binary categorization (uninfected and parasitized). This will direct the use of:

  • Binary crossentropy loss
  • Softmax or sigmoid (will need to alter shape to 1) classification functions

In [49]:
def CNNbuild1(height, width, classes, channels):
    model = Sequential()
    
    inputShape = (height, width, channels)
    chanDim = -1
    
    if K.image_data_format() == 'channels_first':
        inputShape = (channels, height, width)
    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation = 'relu', input_shape = inputShape))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))
    
    model.add(Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation = 'relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))
   
    model.add(Flatten())
    
    model.add(Dense(256, activation = 'relu'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))
    model.add(Dense(classes, activation = 'softmax'))
    
    return model

Model 1 Observations and insights:¶

  • At first observation, it looks as though there were no uninfected data included in the data set. However, it was varified that there are data in both sets within the training and test set.

  • The model did not fit and stopped after only 8 epochs. It is clear the model does not recognize and learn the parasitized images.

  • After doing some research the model appears to be stuck in a "dead neuron" and not advancing. We will try the LeakyReLU threshold. Since this function allows for small values other than zero (i.e. 0.001, the alpha), due to the negtaive slope protion of the function, it may prevent "dead end learning", and allow the learning to advance to the next hidden layer.

  • In the next modelthe activation function is changed from ReLU to LeakyReLU, to determine it's effect on the ability of the model to learn.

  • In addition more neurons are added to the dense layer on the output from 32 to 64.

Model 2: LeakyReLU¶

Using an identical model to Model 1 with the only change in using LeakyReLU activation function in hidden layers.

def CNNbuild2(height, width, classes, channels):
    model = Sequential()
    
    inputShape = (height, width, channels)
    chanDim = -1
    
    if K.image_data_format() == 'channels_first':
        inputShape = (channels, height, width)
    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation = 'LeakyReLU', input_shape = inputShape))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))
    

    model.add(Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation = 'LeakyReLU'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))
    
    model.add(Flatten())
    
    model.add(Dense(256, activation = 'LeakyReLU'))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))
    model.add(Dense(classes, activation = 'softmax'))
    
    return model

Model 2 Observations and Insights:

  • Here we can clearly observe that the model finally did learn and advance once it was able to get past the "dead neuron".

  • Since the only variable we changed here was the activation function from ReLU to LeakyReLU, we can concluide that in this situation, the slightly negative slope of LeakyReLU allowed the model to learn and advance through all the hidden layers.

  • The result of this model was actually quite good, as there was an overall accuracy of 96%, however we would like to have as few false negatives as possible and would like to see our recall/sensitivity increase.

  • It took more time to run this model, therefore may be computationaly more expensive than necessary. Using Batch Normalization and returning to ReLU, which is computationally more simple when used in hidden layers, may help with this.

Model 3: ReLU, BatchNormalization¶

  • ReLU: To make deep layers learn quicker.
  • Batch Normalization: To allow each layer to be standarized and learn independently, which should help learn faster.
  • Increase batch size slightly to also increase speed.

def CNNbuild3(height, width, classes, channels):
    model = Sequential()
    
    inputShape = (height, width, channels)
    chanDim = -1
    
    if K.image_data_format() == 'channels_first':
        inputShape = (channels, height, width)
    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation = 'relu', input_shape = inputShape))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))
    model.add(BatchNormalization(axis = chanDim))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    model.add(Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation = 'relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))
    model.add(BatchNormalization(axis = chanDim))
    model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    #model.add(Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation = 'relu'))
    #model.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))
    #model.add(BatchNormalization(axis = chanDim))
    #model.add(Dropout(0.2))

    model.add(Flatten())
    
    model.add(Dense(256, activation = 'relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization(axis = chanDim))
    model.add(Dropout(0.5)) 
    model.add(Dense(classes, activation = 'softmax'))
    
    return model

Observations and Insights

  • The performance of the model increased substantially by making the modifications.
  • The model fit much more quickly (30s vs. 2 minutes), and is more computationally efficient. This is likely due to the use of ReLU as an activation function and use of Batch Normalization in deep layers.
  • The overall accuracy of Model 3 improved to 97% versus 96% in Model 2, while the number of false negatives decreased, leading to an improvement in recall and precision.
  • We would like to reduce the number of false negatives and increase recall for parasitized even further.

Model 4: Adding additional Layer¶

  • In this iteration we will try to increase the performace even more to reduce false negative rate by adding an additional layer.
  • To mitigate overfitting dropout rate will be increased from 0.2 to 0.3 and added to the additional layer.

# Build model4 with increased dropout
def CNNbuild4(height, width, classes, channels):
    model = Sequential()
    
    inputShape = (height, width, channels)
    chanDim = -1
    
    if K.image_data_format() == 'channels_first':
        inputShape = (channels, height, width)
    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation = 'relu', input_shape = inputShape))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))
    model.add(BatchNormalization(axis = chanDim))
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))

    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation = 'relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))
    model.add(BatchNormalization(axis = chanDim))
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))

    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation = 'relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))
    model.add(BatchNormalization(axis = chanDim))
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))

    model.add(Flatten())
    
    model.add(Dense(512, activation = 'relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization(axis = chanDim))
    model.add(Dropout(0.5)) 
    model.add(Dense(classes, activation = 'softmax'))
    
    return model

# function to plot train and validation accuracy 
def plot_accuracy(history4):
    N = len(history4.history["accuracy"])
    plt.figure(figsize=(7,7))
    plt.plot(np.arange(0, N), history4.history["accuracy"], label="train_accuracy", ls='--')
    plt.plot(np.arange(0, N), history4.history["val_accuracy"], label="val_accuracy", ls='--')
    plt.plot(np.arange(0, N), history4.history["loss"], label="train_loss", ls='--')
    plt.title("Accuracy vs Epoch")
    plt.xlabel("Epochs")
    plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
    plt.legend(loc="upper left")

In [140]:
transfer_layer = vgg.get_layer('block5_pool')
vgg.trainable=False

# Add classification layers on top of it  

x = Flatten()(transfer_layer.output) #Flatten the output from the 3rd block of the VGG16 model
x = Dense(256, activation='relu')(x)
x = Dense(128, activation='relu')(x)
x = Dropout(0.3)(x)
x = Dense(64, activation='relu')(x)
x = BatchNormalization(momentum=0.95, epsilon=0.005,beta_initializer=RandomNormal(mean=0.0, stddev=0.05), gamma_initializer=Constant(value=0.9))(x)
pred = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(x)

model7 = Model(vgg.input, pred) #Initializing the model

Model 7 Observations and insights:

  • There was very poor performance and fit with VGG16.
  • Class was reshaped to 1 to allow for Sigmoid and this did not allow for a fit of the data.
  • The model seemed to have a great deal of difficulty fitting the validation data.
  • Many iterations of this model were attempted, including making the classification layer more complex and more simple.
  • All methods did not help with performance.
  • Next step would be to precisely set the threshold for output using the Sigmoid classification function.

Executive Summary¶

Key Takeaways:

General:

  • More complex models don't always perform the best.
  • Using correctly labeled data can help ensure good model development and performance on training, validation and testing.
  • There is an interaction between deep layer activation function and use of batch normalization.
  • It is possible to design a computationally efficient CNN model for the dection of malaria with a high degree of accuracy, precision and recall.
  • An even more computationally efficint model may be possible to develop over time.
  • Field deployment on smartphones appears to be possible.

Specific:

  • The use of ReLU helps the model run quickly in deep layers During development sometimes learning may get stuck and LeakyReLU can help with this.
  • There is an interaction between the activation function and use of BatchNormalization. These 2 hyperparameters can be tuned to allow for good performance and fast fit. -Sigmoid can be used for binary classification if the data output labes are reshaped. It would be best to set the threshold for use of the Sigmoid classifier in this instance.
  • Batch size has implications for performance and how quickly a model can learn and there is a tradeoff.
  • Dropout and Batch Normalization help prevent overfitting.
  • Adding additional layers helps increase overall performance and learning but comes at a computational cost.

Next Steps:

  • Attempt to reduce computational expense of Model 4 while maintaining high performance.
  • Ths may be achieved by:
    • Removing layers
    • Fewer dense layer neurons
    • Larger batch sizes

  • During development it will be important to ensure good performance metrics are still maintained

  • Experiment with Sigmoid classification function by setting the precise threshold for values to ue for binary classification.

  • Experiment with image size and other output classification methods.

Problem and Solution Summary:

  • The key problem being solved was to develop a method for automatic detection of malaria from images of red blood cells.
  • One key issue was to try to develop a model that could have good performance while using as few computational resources as possible since the rates of Malaria are highest in underdeveoped countries with few resources.
  • The model goal was to have a high rate of accuracy, precision and recall (98% or greater) with very few false negatives.
  • A low number of false negatives is of primary importantance since this is a medical diagnositc tool.
  • Through development it was found that the use of a basic CNN model will work the best for the overall solution.
  • It may be possible to further reduce the computational costs and maintain high performance.
  • This will allow for easy deployment with computational efficiency and still maintain performance.

Recommendations for Implementation:

  • A model similar in structure to Model 4 with correctly labeled images which requires no augmentation is the best model to use for further development and deployment.
  • This includes:
    • 3 2D Convo Layers
      • Maxpooling
      • Dropout 0.3
      • Batch Normalization
      • ReLU for activation function
    • Dene Layer with 512 fully connected neurons
    • 0.5 Drouput
    • Softmax activation function for classification
  • This model attained 99% accuracy, 99% precision, and 99% recall with only 17 false negative images identified from the test set.
  • The use of this model was a basic CNN model and took only 1 minute to fit/run (w/ GPU).
  • The benefits are that malaria may be diagnosed relatively quickly and easily in the field, which will allow for rapid detection of infected patinets such that treatement to be deliered quicker, leading to lower morbidity and mortality.
  • Costs will mostly be in development and testing and deployment on smartphones.
  • There will also have to be field testing of the final equipment and the performance compared to bench testing of the optimal model.
  • The risks are that in striving for computational efficiency and depolyment on a simple platform, the model will not work as well and false negatives, which are the riskiest medicially will result.
